{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16965"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16965"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.07,0.12,0.63,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4356"},{"type":"tags","id":"12143"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46740"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first pregnancy following in vitro fertilisation (IVF) after two years of infertility. An ultrasound scan at 12 weeks confirms a dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy supplements including folic acid and iron. She works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m2. The uterine size is appropriate for gestational age.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely complication to occur in this pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome","Gestational diabetes mellitus","Pre-eclampsia","Preterm birth","Placental abruption"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple risk factors for preterm birth, including a twin pregnancy, IVF conception, advanced maternal age, and nulliparity. Dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies carry a significant risk of preterm birth, with approximately 60% delivering before 37 weeks and 8-12% before 32 weeks gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreterm birth\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely complication given the combination of risk factors. The risk is particularly increased in IVF pregnancies compared to spontaneously conceived twin pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGestational diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in twin pregnancies and with advanced maternal age, but the risk is lower than that of preterm birth in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-eclampsia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in approximately 15-20% of twin pregnancies, which is higher than singleton pregnancies, but still less likely than preterm birth in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwin-to-twin transfusion syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E only occurs in monochorionic pregnancies, not in dichorionic pregnancies as presented here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in multiple pregnancies but occurs in less than 5% of cases, making it less likely than preterm birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this pregnancy should include regular monitoring of cervical length, discussion about signs and symptoms of preterm labour, and consideration of antenatal corticosteroids if preterm birth appears imminent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies have a 60% risk of delivery before 37 weeks gestation.","IVF conception independently increases the risk of preterm birth in multiple pregnancies.","Advanced maternal age and nulliparity are additional risk factors for preterm birth in multiple pregnancies."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Twin and triplet pregnancy [Internet]. London: NICE; 2019 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng137/resources/twin-and-triplet-pregnancy-pdf-66141724389829","Litwinska E, Syngelaki A, Cimpoca B, Frei L, Nicolaides KH. Outcome of twin pregnancy with two live fetuses at 11-13\u2009weeks\u0027 gestation. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 2020 Jan;55(1):32-38. doi: 10.1002/uog.21892. Epub 2019 Dec 13. PMID: 31613412."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16965"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T13:10:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T13:11:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9655"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"